---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../components/docs/CodeBlock.astro";
import ApiTable from "../components/docs/ApiTable.astro";

const sdk = "@ldlework/toybox-sdk";

// Sidebar sections — id must match each <section id> below.
const toc = [
  { id: "overview", label: "Overview" },
  { id: "anatomy", label: "Plugin anatomy" },
  { id: "manifest", label: "The manifest" },
  { id: "exporters", label: "Exporters" },
  { id: "importers", label: "Importers" },
  { id: "panels", label: "UI panels" },
  { id: "host-api", label: "Host API reference" },
  { id: "fs-api", label: "Filesystem API" },
  { id: "report", label: "Reports" },
  { id: "types", label: "Asset & data types" },
  { id: "permissions", label: "Permissions & security" },
  { id: "runtime", label: "How loading works" },
  { id: "dev", label: "Developing a plugin" },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Plugin API — Toybox"
  description="Full reference for writing Toybox import and export plugins: the manifest, the exporter run contract, importer panels, the host API, the filesystem jail, and the shared-runtime model."
>
  <Nav />

  <main class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-6 py-12 md:py-16">
    <div class="mb-12 max-w-3xl">
      <div class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-accent-soft">Reference</div>
      <h1 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-balance md:text-5xl">Plugin API</h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-300 text-pretty">
        Toybox plugins are small JavaScript modules that add <strong>import</strong> and
        <strong>export</strong> formats. A plugin reads the selected assets, gets the host's
        glTF/GLB primitives, and writes files — optionally shipping its own React UI that renders
        with the app's own design system. This page is the complete contract.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="gap-12 lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[200px_minmax(0,1fr)]">
      <!-- Sidebar -->
      <aside class="mb-10 lg:sticky lg:top-8 lg:mb-0 lg:self-start">
        <nav class="flex flex-col gap-1 text-sm">
          {toc.map((t) => (
            <a
              href={`#${t.id}`}
              class="rounded-md px-3 py-1.5 text-slate-400 transition-colors hover:bg-slate-850/70 hover:text-slate-100"
            >
              {t.label}
            </a>
          ))}
        </nav>
      </aside>

      <!-- Content -->
      <div class="min-w-0 max-w-3xl">
        <!-- OVERVIEW ------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="overview" class="scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Overview</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            There are two kinds of plugin. An <strong>exporter</strong> turns the current selection
            into files on disk — a merged <code class="ds-code">.glb</code>, a loose copy, a
            project-specific layout. An <strong>importer</strong> brings new assets <em>into</em> the
            library from some outside source. Both are authored against one package:
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="bash">npm install {sdk}</CodeBlock>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            The package is the plugin <em>contract</em> — manifest types, the <code class="ds-code">ctx</code>
            shapes your code receives, and the <code class="ds-code">define*</code> authoring helpers. You
            install it for types; at runtime the host redirects the import to its own bundled copy, so
            your plugin shares the host's exact instances (one <code class="ds-code">three</code>, one React)
            rather than bundling its own.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- ANATOMY -------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="anatomy" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Plugin anatomy</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            A plugin is a folder under the app's data directory. Each folder's name must equal the
            plugin <code class="ds-code">id</code> in its manifest.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="text" title="<app-data>/plugins/">com.acme.myplugin/
├─ manifest.json        # required — id, kind, permissions, entry/ui
├─ dist/
│  ├─ index.js          # exporter entry module (default-exports run)
│  └─ ui/
│     └─ Export.js      # optional UI panel (default-exports a component)
└─ ...your source</CodeBlock>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            On Windows the data directory is <code class="ds-code">%APPDATA%\com.toybox.app\plugins\</code>;
            on macOS/Linux it's the platform's app-data equivalent. The app discovers plugins at
            startup — a folder with no valid manifest is skipped, never fatal.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- MANIFEST ------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="manifest" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">The manifest</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            <code class="ds-code">manifest.json</code> declares what the plugin is and what it may do.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="json" title="manifest.json">{`{
  "id": "com.acme.myplugin",
  "name": "My Exporter",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "kind": "exporter",
  "entry": "dist/index.js",
  "description": "What this plugin does.",
  "permissions": {
    "rustExport": true,
    "fsWrite": true,
    "fsRead": false
  },
  "ui": {
    "exportPanel": "dist/ui/Export.js"
  }
}`}</CodeBlock>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "id: string", description: "Reverse-DNS identifier. MUST equal the folder name, or the plugin is skipped." },
            { signature: 'kind: "exporter" | "importer"', description: "Which contract the plugin fulfils." },
            { signature: "entry: string", description: "Path (relative to the plugin folder) of the exporter's entry module. Required for exporters; importers are panel-only and may omit it." },
            { signature: "permissions: {…}", description: "Capability flags gating the host API — see Permissions below." },
            { signature: "fields?: FieldSpec[]", description: "Optional declarative config inputs (the zero-code UI path). Ignored when a UI panel is present." },
            { signature: "ui?: { exportPanel?, importPanel? }", description: "Paths to plugin-shipped React panel modules. When present, the host mounts the panel instead of rendering fields." },
          ]} />
        </section>

        <!-- EXPORTERS ------------------------------------------------------ -->
        <section id="exporters" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Exporters</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            An exporter's entry module default-exports the result of <code class="ds-code">defineExporter</code>.
            Its <code class="ds-code">run</code> receives the <code class="ds-code">ctx</code> and the selected
            assets, does its work through the host primitives, and returns a report.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="ts" title="dist/index.js (authored as index.ts)">{`import { defineExporter } from "${sdk}";

export default defineExporter({
  async run(ctx, assets) {
    const { host, fs, config, report } = ctx;

    for (const asset of assets) {
      const glb = await host.assembleGlb(asset.id);          // Uint8Array
      await fs.writeBytes(config.targetDir, asset.name + ".glb", glb);
      report.write(asset.name + ".glb");
    }

    return report.done();
  },
});`}</CodeBlock>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            <code class="ds-code">run</code> is called once per export, with the live selection. Throw to
            fail the run; the host surfaces the message. Respect <code class="ds-code">ctx.signal</code> for
            cancellation on long runs.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="ts">{`run(ctx: ExportCtx, assets: AssetView[]): Promise<ExportReport>`}</CodeBlock>
        </section>

        <!-- IMPORTERS ------------------------------------------------------ -->
        <section id="importers" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Importers</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            Importers are <strong>panel-only</strong> — there is no <code class="ds-code">run</code>. The work
            lives in an <code class="ds-code">importPanel</code> component that picks a source, builds
            <code class="ds-code">SeedEntryInput[]</code>, and hands them to the host via
            <code class="ds-code">ctx.commit</code>. The host merges them into the catalog and refreshes the
            grid.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="ts" title="dist/ui/Import.js (authored as Import.tsx)">{`import { defineImportPanel, type ImportPanelCtx, type SeedEntryInput } from "${sdk}";
import { Stack, Button } from "${sdk}/ui";

export default defineImportPanel(function ImportPanel({ ctx }: { ctx: ImportPanelCtx }) {
  async function go() {
    const dir = await ctx.host.pickDirectory();
    if (!dir) return;
    const entries: SeedEntryInput[] = scanForEntries(dir);  // your logic
    await ctx.commit(entries);                                // host merges + refreshes
    ctx.close();
  }
  return (
    <Stack gap={12}>
      <Button variant="primary" onClick={go}>Import from folder…</Button>
    </Stack>
  );
});`}</CodeBlock>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            The manifest sets <code class="ds-code">"kind": "importer"</code> and
            <code class="ds-code">{`"ui": { "importPanel": "dist/ui/Import.js" }`}</code>; no
            <code class="ds-code">entry</code> is needed.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- PANELS --------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="panels" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">UI panels</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            A panel is a React component that the host mounts in its export or import drawer. It runs on
            the host's <em>exact</em> React instance and renders with the app's design-system primitives
            (<code class="ds-code">{sdk}/ui</code>), so it looks native and hooks work across the boundary.
            Each panel receives a single typed <code class="ds-code">ctx</code> <em>prop</em>.
          </p>

          <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-semibold text-slate-100">Export panel — <code class="ds-code">ExportPanelCtx</code></h3>
          <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            An export panel collects config and pushes it up; it does <em>not</em> write files. The
            host runs the exporter's <code class="ds-code">run</code> later with whatever config the panel
            reported.
          </p>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "host: SlotHost", description: "Render-time reads + OS pickers (see below). The narrow read subset — write primitives fire later, in run." },
            { signature: "shared: { targetDir, preserveStructure }", description: "The host-level export inputs every mode shares." },
            { signature: "setConfig(values, ready): void", description: "Report the panel's collected config and whether it's valid. Call it whenever inputs change; the host's Export button enables on ready." },
          ]} />
          <CodeBlock lang="tsx">{`import { defineExportPanel, type ExportPanelCtx } from "${sdk}";
import { Stack, TextInput } from "${sdk}/ui";
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

export default defineExportPanel(function Panel({ ctx }: { ctx: ExportPanelCtx }) {
  const [subDir, setSubDir] = useState("exported");
  useEffect(() => ctx.setConfig({ subDir }, subDir.length > 0), [ctx, subDir]);
  return (
    <Stack gap={12}>
      <TextInput value={subDir} onChange={(e) => setSubDir(e.currentTarget.value)} />
    </Stack>
  );
});`}</CodeBlock>

          <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-semibold text-slate-100">Import panel — <code class="ds-code">ImportPanelCtx</code></h3>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "host: SlotHost", description: "Same render-time read + picker surface as the export panel." },
            { signature: "commit(entries): Promise<void>", description: "Hand SeedEntryInput[] to the host. It merges them into the catalog and refreshes the grid. Rejects on failure — handle it." },
            { signature: "close(): void", description: "Close the import drawer (typically after a successful commit)." },
          ]} />

          <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-semibold text-slate-100">The render-time host — <code class="ds-code">SlotHost</code></h3>
          <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            Both panel contexts expose the same narrow <code class="ds-code">host</code>: reads and pickers
            only. The gated write/export primitives are deliberately absent during render — they fire at
            run/commit, host-driven.
          </p>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "getSelectedAssets(): AssetView[]", description: "The currently selected catalog assets." },
            { signature: "getAsset(id): AssetView | undefined", description: "Look up one asset by id." },
            { signature: "pickDirectory(): Promise<string | null>", description: "Open the OS folder picker; null if cancelled." },
            { signature: "pickSaveFile(defaultName): Promise<string | null>", description: "Open the OS save-file dialog; null if cancelled." },
          ]} />

          <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-semibold text-slate-100">Declarative fields (no-code path)</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            If a plugin needs only simple inputs, it can skip a custom panel and declare
            <code class="ds-code">fields</code> in the manifest. The host renders each with the matching
            primitive and passes the collected values into <code class="ds-code">config</code>.
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="json">{`"fields": [
  { "key": "subDir", "type": "text", "label": "Subfolder", "default": "exported" },
  { "key": "merge", "type": "checkbox", "label": "Merge into one file", "default": true },
  { "key": "target", "type": "directory", "label": "Output folder", "required": true }
]`}</CodeBlock>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            Field types: <code class="ds-code">text</code>, <code class="ds-code">checkbox</code>,
            <code class="ds-code">select</code>, <code class="ds-code">directory</code>,
            <code class="ds-code">saveFile</code>. A custom panel always wins over fields when both are present.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- HOST API ------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="host-api" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Host API reference</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            <code class="ds-code">ctx.host</code> (an <code class="ds-code">HostApi</code>) is what an exporter's
            <code class="ds-code">run</code> uses to read the catalog and invoke the host's native glTF/GLB
            primitives. The primitive half is gated by the <code class="ds-code">rustExport</code> permission;
            calling a gated method without the grant throws.
          </p>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "getSelectedAssets(): AssetView[]", description: "The live selection (same as the assets argument to run)." },
            { signature: "getAsset(id): AssetView | undefined", description: "Look up one asset by id." },
            { signature: "getParsedGltf(id): Promise<unknown>", description: "The asset's parsed glTF JSON document, for inspection or transformation." },
            { signature: "getAssetUrls(id): Promise<{ gltf, bin, textures }>", description: "Loadable URLs for the asset's files (e.g. to fetch bytes in JS)." },
            { signature: "assembleGlb(id): Promise<Uint8Array>", description: "Bake the asset into a single self-contained binary .glb.", perm: "rustExport" },
            { signature: "performCopy(id, targetDir, stem, preserveStructure): Promise<string[]>", description: "Write a loose copy (.gltf + .bin + textures) under targetDir; returns the relative paths written.", perm: "rustExport" },
            { signature: "transcodeImage(fileName, bytes): Promise<{ mime, bytes }>", description: "Transcode an image through the host (e.g. normalize texture formats).", perm: "rustExport" },
            { signature: "placerMerge(libraryJsonPath, subDirRes, assets): Promise<void>", description: "Godot-specific: create or merge an asset_library.json for the asset_placer addon.", perm: "rustExport" },
          ]} />
        </section>

        <!-- FS API --------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="fs-api" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Filesystem API</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            <code class="ds-code">ctx.fs</code> (an <code class="ds-code">FsApi</code>) is the jailed write
            surface. Writes go through an <code class="ds-code">authorizedRoot</code> — the user-picked target
            directory or save-file the run is scoped to — and any path escaping that root is rejected by the
            host. Writes are gated by the <code class="ds-code">fsWrite</code> permission.
          </p>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "writeBytes(authorizedRoot, path, bytes): Promise<void>", description: "Write binary data at path (relative to or inside authorizedRoot).", perm: "fsWrite" },
            { signature: "writeText(authorizedRoot, path, text): Promise<void>", description: "Write a UTF-8 text file.", perm: "fsWrite" },
            { signature: "writeJson(authorizedRoot, path, value): Promise<void>", description: "Serialize value as pretty JSON and write it.", perm: "fsWrite" },
            { signature: "pickDirectory(): Promise<string | null>", description: "Open the OS folder picker." },
            { signature: "pickSaveFile(defaultName): Promise<string | null>", description: "Open the OS save-file dialog." },
          ]} />
        </section>

        <!-- REPORT --------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="report" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Reports</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            <code class="ds-code">ctx.report</code> accumulates the run's outcome. Record each written file,
            skip, or warning as you go, then return <code class="ds-code">report.done()</code> — the host shows
            the summary.
          </p>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "write(path): void", description: "Record a file you wrote." },
            { signature: "skip(message): void", description: "Record something intentionally skipped." },
            { signature: "warn(message): void", description: "Record a non-fatal warning." },
            { signature: "done(): ExportReport", description: "Finalize and return { written, skipped, warnings }." },
          ]} />
        </section>

        <!-- TYPES ---------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="types" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Asset & data types</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            The read-only view of an asset a plugin sees:
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="ts">{`interface AssetView {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  fileName: string;
  relPath: string;
  pack: string;
  category: string;
  fileset: { gltf: string; bin: string; textures: string[] };
  user: { favorite: boolean; tags: string[] };
  animation: { clipCount: number; clipNames: string[] };
}`}</CodeBlock>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">What an importer produces, and an export run returns:</p>
          <CodeBlock lang="ts">{`interface SeedEntryInput { id: string; pack: string; category: string; file: string; }

interface ExportReport { written: string[]; skipped: string[]; warnings: string[]; }`}</CodeBlock>
        </section>

        <!-- PERMISSIONS ---------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="permissions" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Permissions & security</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            The manifest's <code class="ds-code">permissions</code> gate the host API. A method whose
            capability isn't granted is replaced with a stub that throws — so the manifest is the
            <em>advisory</em> boundary.
          </p>
          <ApiTable rows={[
            { signature: "rustExport", description: "Allows the native glTF/GLB primitives on ctx.host (assembleGlb, performCopy, transcodeImage, placerMerge)." },
            { signature: "fsWrite", description: "Allows ctx.fs.write* (always jailed to the run's authorized root)." },
            { signature: "fsRead", description: "Allows reads through the host." },
          ]} />
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            The <strong>real</strong> boundary is enforced in the host's Rust layer: every write is
            path-jailed to the run's authorized root and rejected if it escapes (no
            <code class="ds-code">..</code>, no absolute path outside the root), and plugin source is served
            from a protocol jailed to the plugins directory. A plugin cannot write outside the folder the
            user picked for the run, regardless of what its manifest claims.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- RUNTIME -------------------------------------------------------- -->
        <section id="runtime" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">How loading works</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            Plugin modules load from a custom <code class="ds-code">plugin://</code> protocol origin served by
            the host (jailed to the plugins directory). Because it's a real origin — not a
            <code class="ds-code">blob:</code> URL — it's subject to the document's import map, which is the
            mechanism that lets your bare imports resolve to the host's shared chunks:
          </p>
          <CodeBlock lang="ts">{`import * as THREE from "three";              // → the host's one three instance
import { useState } from "react";            // → the host's one React
import { defineExporter } from "${sdk}";       // → the host's SDK
import { Button } from "${sdk}/ui";            // → the host's design system`}</CodeBlock>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            So you never bundle <code class="ds-code">three</code>, React, or the SDK into your plugin — you
            import them by bare specifier and the host supplies the single shared instance. This is what
            keeps r3f's <code class="ds-code">instanceof</code> checks working and React hooks valid across the
            app/plugin boundary.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- DEV ------------------------------------------------------------ -->
        <section id="dev" class="mt-14 scroll-mt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Developing a plugin</h2>
          <ol class="mt-4 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-5 leading-relaxed text-slate-300 marker:text-slate-500">
            <li>
              Create a folder with a <code class="ds-code">manifest.json</code> and a TypeScript entry.
              Install <code class="ds-code">{sdk}</code> for types.
            </li>
            <li>
              Build your entry (and any panel) to the <code class="ds-code">dist/</code> paths your manifest
              points at. Keep bare imports — do not bundle <code class="ds-code">three</code>, React, or the SDK.
            </li>
            <li>
              Drop the folder into the app's <code class="ds-code">plugins/</code> directory (or, in a repo
              checkout, link it in). The app discovers it at startup; a load failure shows in the drawer with
              its reason rather than breaking the app.
            </li>
            <li>
              Open the export or import drawer to exercise it. Iterate; reload to pick up a rebuild.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p class="mt-6 leading-relaxed text-slate-300">
            The bundled <strong>Godot asset_placer</strong> exporter is the reference implementation — a
            full exporter with a custom panel — and the best worked example to read alongside this page.
          </p>
        </section>

        <div class="mt-16 border-t border-hairline pt-8">
          <a href={import.meta.env.BASE_URL} class="text-sm text-accent-soft hover:text-white transition-colors">← Back to overview</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style is:global>
  /* Inline-code styling for the docs prose. Matches the ds token palette. */
  .ds-code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85em;
    padding: 0.1em 0.4em;
    border-radius: 0.3em;
    background: var(--color-slate-850);
    color: var(--color-accent-soft);
    white-space: nowrap;
  }
</style>
